TS bolts on a straightforward nominative type system without type unions (or non-nullable types), so it can&#x27;t handle a variable typed as `number | string`, it&#x27;ll immediately drop down to `any`. That is, flow aims to remain useful in the face of more JS idioms. It won&#x27;t make a difference between nullable and non-nullable either, so AFAIK<p><pre><code>    function length(x) {
      return x.length;
    }

    length(null);
</code></pre>
can never be a compile-time error in typescript.

I agree, it would be good to tighten up the terminology. &quot;Weak typing&quot; should be reserved for stuff where the underlying bits can get reinterpreted at will, e.g.:<p><pre><code>    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, 42.0);
</code></pre>
Strong typing means the type of each chunk of memory is known and can&#x27;t be arbitrarily changed, and then static/dynamic refers to how much type information is present at compile time.<p>Might be a losing battle, though. Strong/weak has been overloaded in this way for a long time.
